
[1]estovers

   ESTO'VERS, n. In law, necessaries, or supplies; a reasonable allowance
   out of lands or goods for the use of a tenant; such as sustenance of a
   felon in prison, and for his family, during his imprisonment; alimony
   for a woman divorced, out of her husband's estate.

   Common of estovers is the liberty of taking the necessary wood for the
   use or furniture of a house or farm, from another's estate. In Saxon,
   it is expressed by bote, which signifies more or supply, as house-bote,
   plow-bote, fire-bote, cart-bote, &c.
